project_info.prj_title: Allen Brook watershed restoration & stormwater abatement (phase 2) FY2007
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview Grant is to help satisfy final construction needed to stabilize 2 stormwater generated channels in Williston. Both channels are eroding at an acclerated rate and delivering a formidable amount of sediment and P to Allen Brook.
Objectives Reduce flow volumes and velocities while increasing infiltration and streambank stabilization. Project objectives include: Selective grade control at points of signifciantly active headcuts. Hydrologic balance restoration thru distributed stormwater detention.
Methods Relax gradient at headcut & widen channel to allow stream to meander & achieve fluvial geomorphic equilibrium. Enhance riparian area condition. Install underground stormwater storage tank to redcue velocity

project_info.prj_title: #02 Bacterial Impaired Waters Found in Central Vermont FY2008
project_info.prj_complete_comments: Subrecipient: Friends of the Winooski River
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview Friends of the Winooski River: Detecting, identifying and eliminating (where feasible) illicit discharges to certain bacteria impaired waters found in central Vermont. Locations include: Winooski River in Montpelier, Stevens Branch in Berlin and the Dog River in the Northfield area.
Objectives 1. Comprehensively assess dry-weather flows from storm drain outfalls in three communities discharging to surface waters with documented impairment by indicator bacteria. 2. Produce or verify a GIS data layer of outfall locations in each community. 3. Where outfall monitoring has indicated contamination, assist communities in locating sources of suspected contamination within their storm drainage networks and planning corrective measures.
Methods 1. Record observations and perform basic water quality tests at flowing outfalls during dry weather periods. Testing of flowing outfalls includes: E. coli, optical brighteners, chlorine, specific conductance, temperature, and pH. Existing information on outfall locations will be gathered to guide this effort. 2. Work with each municipality to identify the origins of suspected illicit discharges. 3. Develop plans with the participating municipalities to eliminate the identified pollution sources.

project_info.prj_title: #04 Lake Carmi Phosphorus Reduction Plan (Year 1) FY2008
project_info.prj_complete_comments: Subrecipient: Franklin Watershed Committee
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview The purpose is to reduce phosphorus runoff to Lake Carmi such that nuisance algae blooms no longer occur. It is a multi-year project that will require a significant reduction of phosphorus loading in the waterbody.
Objectives 1. Implement meaningful phophorus and sediment runoff reductions in all source (land use) categories: agriculture; watershed residential; shoreland residential; state; municipal and private roads; and stream stability. 2. Build cooperative relationships with landowners to achieve #1. An important aspect of this cooperation is ensuring all landowners take part in reducing their potential phosphorus and sediment runoff in order to build trust and good will. 3. Leverage other funding sources for project implementation such as CREP, Better Backroads, and EQIP. FWC believes more of these funds can be used in this basin if personnel time is devoted to assisting landowners or the town in applying for and making use of these funds. 4. Provide implementation funds for projects that can be fixed expeditiously or that fall outside of established funding sources such as residential lakeshore re-vegetation and stream-crossing fencing as part of a CREP project. 5. Provide information to landowners regarding good land use practices where use of implementation funds is not appropriate. Explore ways to build participation in voluntary BMPs on all land uses.
Methods 1. Contract a watershed technician to coordinate work between FWC Board of Directors, the Lake Carmi Campers Association and the Town of Franklin. 2. Conduct Action Items -High Priority Actions: Septic system maintenance and outreach to locate and eliminate "hot spots." Shoreland management outreach and erosion and runoff survey of shoreland properties. Complete initial stream surveys. Work one-on-one with farmers and landowners to identify and enable additional phophorus control measures for their farms. 3. Monitor Lake Carmi for phosphorus and algae blooms.

project_info.prj_title: #05 Sediment/Erosion Control Along Portions of Carlisle Hill Road (North Branch Neshobe River) FY2008
project_info.prj_complete_comments: Subrecipient: Town of Goshen
project_info.pst_comment:
Construction of the 200' retaining wall, next to Carlisle Hill Road where the stream bank of the North Branch of the Neshobe River abuts the road shoulder, began the first week of June with the help of Jack Bowen. It had destabilized due to the stream scouring and runoff from the road that had caused channelization and eroded the edge of the road. Eleven loads of large stone (recycled from the blasted from ledge) was used for building material. The wall began at stream-side and rose about 15 high and effectively stabilized the stream bank. When the construction was completed, large stones were placed along the top of the wall as guardrail. A filter fabric and rip-rap was placed along the newly created shoulder for additional stabilization. The total paid to Jack Bowen Excavating was $29,189.00.
Mike Smith was hired for culvert replacement and the placement of stone-lining in the ditches along Carlisle Hill Road. Overall, five culverts were replaced along the segment of the road that runs beside the river. Each culvert had stone headers constructed on the inlets and stone plunge pools at the outlets. Filter fabric was used beneath all of the new construction. Roughly 1,000' of the roadside was also ditched and stone-lined, as well as building stone headers on existing culverts that were not replaced. Mike Smith participated in the BBR Workshop that was hosted on July 14. He did the culvert replacement for the Best Management Practices example while the workshop explained the procedure. All of the ditching, stone-lining, culvert replacements and stream-bank stabilization has been thoroughly tested due to the heavy rainfall experienced during the duration of the project. The total paid to Mike Smith Excavating was $5,355.00. The remaining costs of the project were paid by the Town of Goshen including: culverts, culvert bands, 5-12 stone, and road gravel. There was donated labor and materials that will be included in the final report, along with a more detailed listing of costs and pictures for documentation.
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview The present conditions of the ditches and culverts along the Crlisle Hill Road, in the Town of Goshen, create runoff that degrades the water qaulity of the North Branch of the Neshobe River and creates a danger to motorists.
Objectives 1.Properly retain the road embankment and stabilize streambanks: This project will address the water quality problems by replacing the existing culverts that have failed, adding stone lined ditches, rebuilding stone headwalls, creating rock aprons and retaines, as well as installing plunge pools at culvert outlets. 2. Public access: Efforts will make the gravel road easier to maintain increasing road safety. 3. Riparian plantings will help to ensure better aquatic habitat. 4. Reduce cost of maintaining the road in the future. 5. Educate road crews and other town selectboard members.
Methods 1. Replacement (5 of 11 culverts) -Culvert in front of Goshen Town Clerks office -Stone lined ditch installed on the west side for 200 feet -North: culvert heaved up, in need of replacement -North: squashed culvert, in need of replacement -Stone lined ditch along gravel roadway on west side (3,000 feet) -Rock retainment and rock curtain drain along 75 feet of destablized stream bank -Two culverts on northern end -Rock aprons, retainers and rock lined plunget pools are to be installed along the roadway with the culverts
2. Education -Educational workshop for area road crews and other town slectboard members by providing an on-site demonstration of proper culvert replacement techniques, rock-lining of ditches, and culvert heardwall stabliziation 3. Measurable Goals for Water Quality -Physical monitoring (sedimentation analysis, pebble count) -Chemical water quality -Biological monitoring

project_info.prj_title: #06 West Shore Road: Lakeshore Sediment/Erosion Control Demonstration Project FY2008
project_info.prj_complete_comments: Subrecipient: Town of Isle La Motte
project_info.pst_comment: The project has initiated the educational aspect of the implementation plan. Construction was delayed due to issues with the surrounding land owners. Bank stabilization construction completed with toe of slope hardening, jutte matting & willow stakes. Project also resulted in passage of an ordinance against roadside vegetation cutting.
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview The purpose of the project is to demonstrate lake-friendly erosion control techniques along Lake Champlain.
Objectives 1. Implement an erosion control demonstration project on West Shore Road. 2. Conduct public outreach to build an understanding about these methods and the importance of setbacks and buffers along the lakeshore. 3. Additional outreach includes the development of a release for public comment and a draft land use regulation restricting or prohibiting land clearing in sensitive shoreland areas in the future. 4. Improve Water Quality by: -Fostering practices and policies that promote shoreline stability -Advance implementation of bio-technical erosion control practices along the Lake Champlain shoreline -Encourage property owners to consider the unintended impacts of removing shoreline vegetation
Methods 1. Town of Isle La Motte will construct a sediment/erosion control project at a pre-determined locaiton and conduct outreach to community residents and others highlighting the importance of setbacks and buffers. 2. Construction activities will take place in the town highway right-of-way. A written agreement will be used where private property owners will be impacted by the construction; this agreement will define project expectations and the responsibilities of the Town and property owner. -The contractor hired through this process will place the rip rap toe, construct the geo-grid fabric embankment, and stabilize the project until the brush layering can be installed. -Vermont Youth Conservation Corps will be solicited to help with the project. -The Northwest Regional Planning Commision will be requested for assistance in public outreach. 3. Measures of Success Yearly visual inspections and one and two year intervals following construction to document that the erosion control method continues to work as designed.

status_history.pst_comment: The project has initiated the educational aspect of the implementation plan. Construction is delayed due to issues with the surrounding land owners. After more evaluation, it is expected that additional sediment controls will need to be installed.

project_info.prj_title: #07 Rock River/Saxe Brook Sediment Abatement Demonstration and Technical Assistance Program (year 2) FY2008
project_info.prj_complete_comments: Subrecipient: Friends of Missisquoi Bay
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview -The purpose of this grant project is to demonstrate, evaluate and provide technical assistance on the effectiveness of a variety of low cost, on the field practices and injection in reducing nonpoint pollution in the Rock River and Saxe Brook watersheds, as well as demonstrating the potential benefits of such practices to other landowners. -Field erosion control measures effectiveness and ability to fit into farm management practices
Objectives 1. Identify sites prone to sediment loss and work out arrangements with the landowners/custom operators to minize costs and yield risks. 2. Implement field practices: such as cover cropping, strip cropping, cross-slope tillage, zone tilling, subsoil rippers, grassed waterways, filter strips, utilization of shorter season corn, crop rotation and manure management. 3. Demonstrate/Evaluate Effectiveness and Benefits. 4. Provide Technical Assistance.
Methods 1. Building on the 2007 grant by continuing to engage an agricultural expert within the Northern Lake Champlain basin to coordinate farm practice projects. 2. Demonstrate effectiveness of these low-cost measures in reducing direct runoff of fine sediments and nutrients. 3. Continue to involve public participation in project and informational sharing.
project_info.lreduction_comments:
0.3 to 2.0 tons/ac per yr soil loss reduction
527 * 0.3 = 158 tons sediment 527 * 2 = 1054 tons sediment 606 tons sediment reduction (ave value)

status_history.pst_comment: Covercrop was planted on 100 acres of the most vulnerable lands to erosion in the Fall of 2007. Seeding included: winter rye, oats and winter triticale. After observation, in the fall 2008, it was decided that the use of winter rye by the farmers would be need to implemented by October 10. The spring of 2008 was used to promote other field pracitices that would reduce sediment and phosphorus pollution (focus on: reduced tillage planting and sub-soil riprap). Also completed during the Fall of 2008, work was done with the Farmers Watershed Alliance to contact farmers and promote overcropping. Sign-up for the program, based on a first come first serve basis, lead to the siging of 12 farmers with a total of 527 acres. With this participation, it is estimated that there will be a result of between 158 to 1,054 tons of soil.

project_info.prj_title: Erosion/sediment control on rural roads in northwestern VT
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview The Northwest Regional Planning Commission will use grant funds to develop and offer a series of trainings for municipal road crews. Each training will focus on a specific technique or material that can be used to reduce the WQ impacts arising from rural town roads. The need for these trainings was determined following discussions with local road foreman and staff of the Better Backroads Program. This element will be modeled after a successful road crew workshop offered by the Subrecipient and its project partners in spring 2010.
Objectives This project will achieve the following objectives: 1. Implement at least ten demonstrations of best management practices that reduce the impact of rural town roads on water quality in the region. 2. Train local road crews to implement these practices and improve their level of comfort with materials or practices they have not previously used. 3. Accelerate the adoption of practices from the Better Backroads Manual in northwestern Vermont. 4. Get feedback from road crews following implementation of these projects to determine which are the most appropriate and replicable in the region and to identify challenges to utilizing certain techniques or materials.
Methods The project will measure success based on the following: evaluations provided by workshop attendees; the knowledge and capacity of municipal road crews to identify appropriate locations and implement erosion control practices along public roadways; before and after photos and maps of at least 10 implemented demonstrations; and the number of projects deployed by road crews following their participation in this project.

project_info.prj_title: Simple fixes/land treatments on selected small farms
project_info.pst_comment: As of status date, VACD's indirect rate has not been approved by DEC. Consequently, grant agreement has not been authorized.
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview The VT Association of Conservation Districts has indicated the purpose of this grant project is to assist farms with land treatment that are specific sources of agriculture NPS pollution in a number of selected 303D waterbodies and to work with these farmers to design and then implement simple cost-effective practices and mitigations to reduce the phosphorus impacts from these farms.
Objectives The objective is to assist and facilitate the development and completion of the identified practices on 6 farms that will have immediate and direct impacts leading to the reduction of pollution in the identified waterbodies while creating a model that may have transferability to other small farm operations that have similar resource concerns.
Methods VACD has identified 6 farms within impaired waterbodies (see State 2008 303d list of impaired waters) that are having detrimental impact on these waterbodies. VACD has approached farmers within their designated service areas to enlist their commitment to work on specific issues identified during on-farm visits. From those visits VACD documented the problems photographically and developed and proposed low-cost simple solutions to these problems. From this process VACD has developed a plan for mitigation for each farm and the funding to support the implementation of these solutions. VACD intends to document the work culminating in the development of an audio-visual or web-based product to showcase and highlight the work completed.

project_info.prj_title: youth based watershed restoration
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview The VT Youth Conservation Corps will use grant funds to complete over 165 weeks of high-priority conservation work statewide, with a number of projects focusing specifically on NPS pollution, mitigation, and control. As part of the project selection process, VYCC works closely with natural resource professionals to identify projects of the highest need. In many cases, VYCC seeks the advice of Agency of Natural Resources staff during this process. VYCC has a long-standing history of successfully completing watershed /conservation projects statewide.
Objectives VYCC's Watershed Restoration Program under this grant has the following goals: To provide a large labor force to tackle more priority projects over a broad geographic area To provide a rich educational work and learning experience for Vermont youth by exposing them to water resource management projects To provide tangible results and to continue to address damage to water bodies statewide that provide critical habitat as well as other ecological, recreational, and scenic values To expand the service to new regions in Vermont in order to broaden exposure and community education about watershed resource issues To expose youth to watershed resource management and river corridor restoration through direct participation in a variety of priority conservation projects To promote inter-municipal cooperation and protection efforts focusing on the management of shared river resources through the completion of projects that incorporate and benefit multiple towns To augment the nationally recognized environmental education program which incorporates daily writing, reading, and discussion with valuable hands-on learning experiences in water resource protection and non-point source remediation To enhance current partnerships To encourage stronger relationships between watershed associations and area residents regarding watershed resource protection and management To demonstrate a strong public/private partnership as evidenced by wide-ranging financial (and in-kind) support for the program from state, federal, corporate, foundation, and individual sources.
Methods Projects under this grant in 2010 (or spring 2011) will take place in the following watersheds: Allen Brook, Muddy Brook, Crosby Brook, White and Connecticut River Basins, Winooski River Basin, St. Albans Bay, and Otter Creek.

project_info.prj_title: Urban tree canopy and stormwater management
project_info.prj_complete_comments: Design & permitting issues resulted in grant project mofifications: City of St Albans used $6,000. City of Burlington used $25,193.
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview City of St Albans will use grant funds to increase its urban tree canopy (UTC) in a portion of the City. The City will implement the use of silva cells, or a similar technology, and install street trees along Main Street between Fairfield Street and Hudson Street. These trees and associated silva cells will be positioned to accept runoff from Main Street and/or adjacent sidewalks and buildings and will demonstrate the link between urban trees and stormwater management within the Stevens Brook watershed. Trees will be installed in summer 2011. As part of this project and to help protect existing trees from future development, City will examine its site plan review requirements within its zoning regulations. City is encouraged to propose revised site plan review requirements for public review and comment.
Objectives This project will achieve four objectives: 1.Increase the urban tree canopy in the City of St. Albans. 2.Demonstrate the use of innovative technologies that improve the health and success of urban trees. 3.Examine narrative and intent of existing site plan review requirements and propose revisions for consideration. 4.Develop expertise in urban forestry within the City Public Works Department.
Methods The project will measure success based on the following: the level of treatment achieved by new street trees installed (treatment will include both estimated volume treated and pollutants removed). the replicability of the street tree installation on other City streets. the number of citizens and municipal officials educated about the demonstration project modifications needed to the Citys site plan review requirements in order to better protect existing trees from future developments. knowledge & capacity of City staff and citizens regarding urban forestry and tree maintenance.

project_info.prj_title: Trees for basin #7 streams
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview Lamoille County Natural Resources Conservation District, will use grant funds to continue expanding Trees for Streams program throughout the Lamoille River watershed area and to target specific areas with partners, to adopt areas of concerns that are outliers, and to provide assistance to those that require expertise for the program such as Orleans County District in the headwaters and Wild Branch sub-watersheds. In addition, L-NRCD will tie in other river related projects presently in the works, when applicable, to broaden the effectiveness for the programs overall success.
Objectives Specific objectives for this project include: Utilize site selection methodology and increase outreach to landowners in the Lamoille watershed through the expanded partnership. Select priority sites and forge buffer agreements with landowners. Orchestrate the ordering, storing and planting of trees. Organize, train and support student, and citizen volunteer planting teams. Publicize the planting program to generate interest from volunteers, and as a way to educate the general population about the importance of riparian buffers. Design and install site-specific vegetated buffers. Document and evaluate the program.
Methods Starting in fall 2010 and in cooperation with the State to prioritize the sites, L-NRCD will lead partners in identifying projects specific to those outlined utilizing the existing site selection methodology. Additional landowner outreach (from those not previously identified) will begin thereafter to line up site visits and develop agreements with landowners for buffer plantings and cost sharing. L-NRCD will also work with the Johnson State College students to sample specific sites for physical, chemical and/or biological attributes. Over the winter, landowner site maps will be created, buffers will be designed, and materials ordered. In spring 2011, planting days will be coordinated, including a number of community planting days interfaced with watershed outreach. Final evaluation and reporting will occur in fall 2011.

project_info.prj_title: Model shoreland ordinance development
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview The Vermont League of Cities & Towns will use grant funds to help further protect lake and pond water quality from NPS pollution resulting from lakeshore development pressure through implementation of lakeshore protection regulations.
Objectives Objectives are: Produce a Model Shoreland District Ordinance that can be customized to target specific problems and circumstances unique to individual towns. Produce an accompanying technical paper describing the water quality benefits of lakeshore protection and illustrating how to create an effective shoreland protection ordinance using the Model as a guide. Promote the NPS treatment goals listed below through education, outreach and technical assistance. Encourage and assist in the adoption of a regulatory framework that provides lakeshore protection at the local level.
Methods VLCT will develop a Model Shoreland District Ordinance and accompanying technical paper providing a description of the problem with applicable research data as well as a discussion of how towns can effectively use the model ordinance to fit their individual needs and circumstances. The Water Quality Benefits of Lakeshore Protection Creating an Effective Shoreland Protection Ordinance
The Model Shoreland District Ordinance will be adaptable to the following shoreland district alternatives: Shoreland Overlay District Separate Shoreland District Shoreland Conservation District Shoreland Design Review District
The model shoreland district ordinance will be applicable to all lakes, ponds and reservoirs that a municipality chooses to include for protection. The model ordinance is meant to assist communities throughout the entire State.

project_info.prj_title: Coordination for Lake Carmi P TMDL implementation

project_info.prj_overview:
Overview Franklin Watershed Committee will use grant funds to help reduce phosphorus runoff to Lake Carmi by continuing the coordinating services of a paid watershed coordinator. The benefits of this dedicated time and energy have paid off in increased attendance to meetings, improved relations with land owners and town representatives, and increased productivity and visibility of the group itself. This agreement represents the third year of a multi-year project that will be required in order to reduce phosphorus loading sufficiently to realize WQ improvements and TMDL objectives.
Objectives Project tasks and objectives are: 1.Help to identify and develop meaningful phosphorus and sediment runoff reduction projects in all source (land use) categories: agriculture; watershed residential; shoreland residential; state, municipal and private roads; and stream stability. 2.Build cooperative relationships with landowners to achieve #1. An important aspect of this cooperation is ensuring all landowners take part in reducing their potential phosphorus and sediment runoff in order to build trust and good will. 3.Leverage other funding sources for project implementation such as from Natural Resources Conservation Service and Better Backroads. Subrecipient and State believe more of these funds can be used in this lake watershed to reduce phosphorus if personnel time is devoted to assisting landowners or the town in applying for and making use of these funds. 4.Seek out and, if successful, manage and provide implementation funds for phosphorus reduction projects that can be fixed expeditiously or that fall outside of established funding sources such as residential lakeshore re-vegetation and stream-crossing fencing. 5.Provide information to landowners regarding good phosphorus reduction land use practices where use of implementation funds is not appropriate. Explore ways to build participation in voluntary best management practices on all land uses.
Methods Outreach to watershed landowners iIentify priority projects. Assist with NPS project implementation.

project_info.prj_title: Tri-district cover cropping incentive program
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview The project involved providing one-time incentive payments and administrative coordination for farmers to cover-crop tillable acreage, in an effort to protect nearby waterways from nutrient runoff, erosion and NPS pollution arising from agriculture. Due to the success of the NRCD's previous cover cropping programs, W-NRCD used grant funds to broaden the partnerships, the service area, as well as the overall deliverables to support and maximize the reduction of NPS pollution through its 2009 Cover Cropping Program. The 2009 program will include the Winooski, White River and Caledonia County Conservation Districts and affect a limited amount of land in five watersheds: Upper Winooski (Washington County), White River, Upper Lamoille (in Caledonia County), Passumpsic River, and Basin 14 Little Rivers.
Objectives Objectives of 2009 Cover Cropping Program (CCP) will include: Cover crop 1,000 acres of high priority tilled cropland across the highlighted 5 watersheds. Advertise the program in local papers, agricultural publications and through mailings to all commodity crop growers farming within the proposed project area. Distribute applications for 2009 CCP as well as the VT Agency of Agricultures Farm Agronomic Practices (FAP) program. The VT Agency of Agriculture (VAA) will be signing an agreement with Conservation Districts for this program to secure $30,000 worth of FAP payments as contributing match farmer cost-share incentive for the CCP. With technical assistance from USDA NRCS the W-NRCD and involved Districts will prioritize applicants based on those lands which are most erodible and with the closest proximity to waterways and impaired waterways. The willingness of farmers to employ practices that help maximize the reduction of NPS pollution will also be taken into account. Landowners will be asked to consider best management cropping practices that help reduce NPS, such as: shorter season corn, minimum tillage practices, early seed application and strategies for springtime winter rye incorporation. Provide incentive payments in the amount of $30/acre from the States FAP program to cover the costs of seed, and an additional payment of $18/acre from this grant to cover seed application and incorporation costs. The amount of $18/acre is based on the price from custom applicators for minimum tillage practices, such as direct drill seeding of the rye. Coordinate seed purchasing and application services, to ensure bulk rates and coordination logistics as an additional incentive for farmers to get involved in the program.
Methods Beginning during the early summer months of 2009, the W-NRCD and other participating Conservation Districts will advertise and distribute mailings to include applications to the CCP as well at the the VAAs Farm Agronomic Practice program (FAP). There will be a deadline in early July for submission of the applications. Bulk orders of winter rye seed will also be reserved at this time. Applicants and their enrolled fields with be reviewed and undergo a prioritization process. W-NRCD agrees to seek out and enroll into the CCP as many operators located within impaired watersheds of the project area (i.e. Folsom Brook, Tabor Brook, Ticklenaked Pond watershed).
Selected applicants will be contacted and strategies will be discussed to achieve the highest level of NPS pollution reduction. In August, coordination of seed application will take place collaboratively with the farmer and local custom applicators, where necessary. All applicants will be encouraged to have fields ready for cover cropping in September. To ensure the highest degree of success, planting of cover crops under this grant will be done before 10/10/09 and, where practicable, cover crop seeds shall be incorporated on their application. In October and November, site visits will take place to check on the success of cover cropping on the enrolled fields, and the number of acres will be documented. Incentive payments will be processed in early winter 2009.

project_info.prj_title: stormwater disconnection in Rutland City
project_info.prj_complete_comments: end date extended from 9/30/13 to 6/1/14.
project_info.pst_comment: extended end date to 6/2014 arising from unanticpated delays and staffing issues
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview Project is to focus on disconnection of rooftop runoff from the stormwater drainage system as a way to reduce the volume of water flowing into the Moon Brook (303d water), thereby limiting erosion and biological contamination.
Objectives Project has three objectives: 1) to determine the amount of rooftop runoff that is at present directly connected to the drainage system and its impact on water quality in Moon Brook; 2) to implement redirection of downspouts to improved lawn area on at least 13 properties; and, 3) develop materials to educate the public on why rooftop disconnection is important (printed materials will be mailed in quarterly tax bills to residents in the City of Rutland).
Methods The project will include collecting information to better identify and coordinate an effective message to encourage disconnection of rooftop runoff and provide outreach materials to support an educational campaign. The education campaign will focus residents attention on the problem of stormwater volume and encourage them to choose one or more practices that will best suit their situation. Part of the educational campaign will include developing a draft ordinance for disconnection of future development. Funding from the grant will pay to develop educational materials and staff time to educate and assist residents in identifying appropriate practices for their site. In addition, funds to hire a consultant will be needed to better refine a message and create outreach materials. Staff time will also be needed to analyze existing survey data and to conduct additional survey work in Rutland City. This survey will give the municipality a clear picture of what is happening on the ground and what can reasonably be achieved with a disconnection program.

project_info.prj_title: trees for Lamoille River basin streams - expansion
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview Project is to enable L-NRCD to continue expanding its so-called `Trees for Streams program throughout the Lamoille River watershed area.
Objectives Specific objectives for this project include: Utilize site selection methodology and increase outreach to landowners in the Lamoille watershed through the expanded partnership. Select priority sites and forge buffer agreements with landowners. Orchestrate the ordering, storing and planting of trees. Organize, train and support student, and citizen volunteer planting teams. Publicize the planting program to generate interest from volunteers, and as a way to educate the general population about the importance of riparian buffers. Design and install site-specific vegetated buffers. Document and evaluate the program.
Methods Convene meeting with partners to utilize methodology for site selection and prioritization. Conduct landowner outreach in priority locations, negotiate buffer agreements, conduct site visits & develop preliminary buffer design. Coordinate the ordering, storing and delivery of plants for spring buffer projects. Coordinate plantings through recruitment of volunteer labor for buffer projects, offer educational opportunities for school groups, build community support for buffers. Implement buffer projects on scheduled planting days (cost includes plants/materials) Convene a meeting of all the partners to compile data, evaluate the program and develop a strategy for improvements and further expansion of the program.

project_info.prj_title: Crosby Brook floodplain and buffer restoration
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview Reduce sediment and thermal loading to Crosby Brook and downstream waterways, improve habitat, and protect infrastructure (e.g., adjoining properties threatened by bank erosion).
Objectives Specific project objectives include: 1. Avoid additional downstream loading of sediment, as well as ongoing incision and associated channel evolution processes (e.g., widening and continuing bank erosion). 2. Restore natural riparian buffer conditions along the channel to improve habitat. 3. Protect nearby infrastructure from future damage due to advancing erosion.
Methods 1. Identify alternatives for buffer and floodplain restoration. Prepare concept sketches; Assess hydrology and hydraulics; Estimate rough construction costs; Select alternative. Permitting, Final Designs & Specifications. According to the alternatives analysis and final plans, re-grade floodplain, stabilize banks, and plant riparian buffer with native woody vegetation. Hold a public meeting to explain the project background and educate Putney Road businesses about nonpoint source pollution, corridor plan and fluvial erosion hazards.
project_info.lreduction_comments: 2 areas of Crosby Brook bank stabilization & restoration: 1) 150 ft3 sediment/yr 2) 20 ft3 sediment/yr = 170 ft3 200 lb/ft3 = 17 tons/yr

project_info.prj_title: Englesby Brook - effectiveness of low cost, low tech practices in reducing stormwater runoff
project_info.prj_complete_comments: no planned watershed modeling done given few infiltration samples, widespread nature of disturbed soils and dry weather.
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview Within Englesby Brook watershed (640 acres) develop, test, and implement strategies for disconnecting direct connections to the storm sewer system and improving compacted soils, increasing their ability to infiltrate stormwater and improve water quality.
Objectives Project activities to serve as a demonstration of LID techniques. The information derived from the assessments will be available for use by other municipalities and the public to increase awareness of the completed and evaluated practices.
Methods Sub-grantee will: Establish a target suite of low-tech, low-cost practices for the Englesby Brook watershed that will reduce/delay stormwater inflow into the Citys storm sewer system, including: downspout disconnections, curb and gutter turnouts, soil amendment, soil aeration, and vegetation alteration. Identify specific sites/areas within the Englesby Brook watershed to implement low-cost practices with help from City of Burlington and South Burlington staff. Work with a contractor to complete an initial assessment of infiltration and hydrology at each site, using a combination of inspections, soil analysis, and modeling. Modeling (use of TR-55 or SWMM ) will be used to compare current conditions to future, idealized conditions assuming full implementation. Assessment will be done for at least five sufficiently different sites (ie land use, lot imperviousness, zoning district) within the watershed. Reach out and work with landowners to maximize implementation of the low-tech, low-cost practices on residential properties and city-owned green belts. Complete a follow-up assessment to evaluate the effectiveness of the practices, compare effectiveness with the level of effort required to achieve implementation (e.g., cost/benefit of each practice on a per acre basis) and, in turn, define reasonable expectations for resulting reductions in stormwater management.

status_history.pst_comment: amendment extended end date; behind schedule with some tasks due to weather and infiltration evaluation component.

project_info.prj_title: reducing WQ impacts from our local roads - workshop series and implementation (yr 2)
project_info.pst_comment: extended end date to accomodate staffing changes & unanticipated delays
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview Develop & conduct a series of trainings for municipal road crews. Each training will focus on a specific technique or material that can be used to reduce WQ impacts arising from rural town roads. The need for these trainings was determined following discussions with local road foreman and staff of the Better Backroads Program. Effort is modeled after a successful road crew workshop offered by the Sub-grantee after a 2010 Section 319 grant agreement.
Objectives This project will achieve the following objectives: 1.Implement at least twelve (12) demonstrations of best management practices that reduce the impact of rural municipal and private roads on water quality in the region. 2.Train local road crews to implement these practices and improve their level of comfort with materials or practices they have not previously used. 3.Train owners and managers of private roads and driveways on best management practices to preserve the infrastructure and reduce negative water quality impacts. 4.Reduce erosion and runoff problems from private roads and driveways. 5.Accelerate the adoption of road related erosion control practices from the Better Backroads Manual in northwestern Vermont. 6.Get feedback from road crews following implementation of these projects to determine which are the most appropriate and replicable in the region and to identify challenges to utilizing certain techniques or materials.
Methods Communicate with project partners to identify specific workshop topics and establish a schedule Hold at least 3 workshops for local road crews, each focused on a particular practice. Provide the necessary materials to each town who attended a workshop to enable the town to implement a small-scale demonstration in their community. Hold two workshops for private road and driveway owners and provide free on-site consultations to two workshop participants. Conduct outreach, publicizing the projects completed by the private property owners and municipalities. NRPC will also solicit feedback from each participating municipality and property owners to learn about their experience implementing the practices. Provide technical assistance to municipalities seeking grants to implement additional projects.

project_info.prj_title: simple P mitigation projects for certain small farms (yr 2)
project_info.prj_complete_comments: completed project involved land treatments on 5 farms on 3 impaired waters (03-08, 05-07 and 06-05). treatments included: animal trail, fencing, clean water diversion, watering source, roof runoff diversion.
project_info.pst_comment: project involved 5 farms affecting 3 impaired waters (03--08, 05-07 and 06-05). Treatments installed: clean water diversion, animal trail, fencing, water diversion, watering source, roof runoff diversion
project_info.prj_overview:
Overview Assist certain pre-selected farms with land treatment that are specific sources of agriculture nonpoint source pollution in certain 303D listed impaired waterbodies. Work with these farmers to design and then implement simple cost-effective practices and mitigations to reduce the phosphorus impacts from these farms.
Objectives To assist and facilitate the development and completion of the identified practices on five (5) farms that will have immediate and direct impacts leading to the reduction of pollution in the identified waterbodies while creating a model that may have transferability to other small farm operations that have similar resource concerns.
Methods Subrecipient has identified five farms within impaired waterbodies that are having detrimental impact on these waterbodies. Subrecipient has approached farmers within their designated service areas to enlist their commitment to work on specific issues identified during on-farm visits. From those visits Subrecipient documented the problems photographically and developed and proposed low-cost simple solutions to these problems. From this process Subrecipient has developed a plan for mitigation for each farm and the funding to support the implementation of these solutions. Subrecipient intends to document the work culminating in the development of an audio-visual or web-based product to showcase and highlight the work completed.
project_info.lreduction_comments: pollutant loading reduction estimates provided once project completed. Loading estimates for completed projects totaled 225 lb P/yr and 235 tons sediment/yr.
